## What Each Agent Produces

### Agent 1 â€” PRD
- Executive summary
- Problem statement
- Goals & success metrics
- User personas
- User stories with acceptance criteria
- Feature requirements (MVP vs Phase 2)
- Technical constraints
- Competitive landscape
- Open questions & risks

### Agent 3 â€” Screen Architecture & Governance
- **Screen inventory** â€” every screen with ID, states, component deps, MVP flag, status tag
- **User flow map** â€” Mermaid.js diagram (paste into FigJam directly)
- **Figma file architecture** â€” exact page/frame structure for free seat (2 files, 3 pages each)
- **Governance document** â€” component health statuses, versioning, decision log, monthly ritual, GitHub structure

### Agent 2 â€” Design System
- **Design system spec** â€” principles, color system with WCAG 2.2 AA ratios, typography, spacing, radius, shadows, icons, motion, accessibility, component library
- **tokens.json** â€” W3C DTCG 2025.10 standard, imports directly into Figma via Tokens Studio (free plugin)
- **README.md** â€” plain-language guide for designers and developers

---

## Figma MCP Workflow (After All 3 Agents)

Once your Figma files are set up using Agent 3's architecture plan and Agent 2's token system:

| Task | What to do |
|---|---|
| Inspect a Figma frame | Share URL â†’ Claude reads nodes, layout, tokens |
| Generate component code | Share frame URL â†’ Claude outputs React Native + Tailwind |
| Check design vs spec | Share URL â†’ Claude compares against design system |
| Verify token usage | Share URL â†’ Claude reads Figma variables and checks consistency |

**Example prompt:**
> "Here's my Figma frame for the Home screen: [URL]. The design system spec is in this conversation. Generate a React Native + Tailwind component for the DepartureBoardRow in the populated state."

